lpha-1 and beta-1 receptors","Beta-2 receptors","Both beta-1 and beta-2 receptors equally","Beta-1 receptors","Beta-2 and beta-3 receptors"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECardioselective beta blockers primarily target \u003Cstrong\u003Ebeta-1 receptors\u003C/strong\u003E, which are predominantly found in cardiac tissue. This selectivity helps reduce unwanted effects on other beta receptor subtypes. Examples of this drug class include atenolol, bisoprolol and metoprolol. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlpha-1 and beta-1 receptors\u003C/strong\u003E describes combined alpha-beta blockers like carvedilol, which are not cardioselective agents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-2 receptors\u003C/strong\u003E are found mainly in bronchial smooth muscle and blood vessels, and are not the primary target of cardioselective agents. Blocking them may cause bronchospasm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoth beta-1 and beta-2 receptors equally\u003C/strong\u003E describes non-selective beta blockers like propranolol, which can cause more respiratory side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-2 and beta-3 receptors\u003C/strong\u003E are not the target of any current therapeutic beta blockers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cardioselective beta blockers primarily block beta-1 adrenergic receptors found in cardiac tissue.","Beta-1 receptors mediate heart rate and contractility, while beta-2 receptors mediate bronchodilation and vasodilation."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54155"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17120"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54155"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T11:02:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T11:02:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9810"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68698"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovascular","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position"